  <body>
    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Dubious Honor: Lowest Rating Ever</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Richard Sandomir</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Sandomir, Richard</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New York Yankees-New York Mets Subway Series is lowest-rated televised World Series ever (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Mets-Yankees Subway Series concluded with a 13.1 Nielsen rating with a 21 share on Thursday night, the best performance of the five-game series, but too small to prevent it from becoming the lowest-rated World Series ever.</p>
        <p>The game's rating started slowly, with a 7.5 from 8:21 to 8:30, but peaked with a 16.0 from 11:30 to midnight.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The Mets-Yankees Subway Series concluded with a 13.1 Nielsen rating with a 21 share on Thursday night, the best performance of the five-game series, but too small to prevent it from becoming the lowest-rated World Series ever.</p>
        <p>The game's rating started slowly, with a 7.5 from 8:21 to 8:30, but peaked with a 16.0 from 11:30 to midnight.</p>
        <p>The five-game, 12.4 average rating represents a 12 percent drop from a 14.1 for the 1998 Yankees-Padres World Series, until now the lowest-rated fall classic. The Subway Series also suffered a 23 percent tumble in the ratings from a 16.0 registered by the Yankees' four-game sweep of the Braves last year.</p>
        <p>Each national rating point equals about 1.02 million television households.</p>
        <p>Richard Sandomir</p>
        <p>BASEBALL: NOTEBOOK</p>
      </block>
